A physical disk is actual hardware device that stores data in a computer or server that stores the data permanently 
means the data remains even after the device is powered off

A partition is a logical section of a physical disk (HDD or SSD) 
It allows one physical disk (HDD or SSD) to be split into multiple seperate sections and each section is treated as each independent disk

A filesystem is the structure that allows linux to store, organize and access the files on a disk or partition 
It defines how data is written, stored, retreived and organized

Mount points in linux  are the directories where the filesystem is attached so that it contents become accessible to the system 

Disk Usage shows how much storage space is used on the disk

